    <example id="fs-id1843505">
    <title>Calculating the Number of Molecules in a Cubic Meter of Gas</title>
    <para id="import-auto-id2919471">How many molecules are in a typical object, such as air in a tire? We can use the ideal gas law to give us an idea of how large <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>N</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> typically is.</para>
    <para id="import-auto-id2677390">Calculate the number of molecules in a cubic meter of air at standard temperature and pressure (STP), which is defined to be <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>0</m:mn><m:mtext>º</m:mtext><m:mtext>C</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> and atmospheric pressure.</para>
    <para id="import-auto-id2919757">
      <title>Strategy</title>
    </para>
    <para id="import-auto-id2717709">Because pressure, volume, and temperature are all specified, we can use the ideal gas law <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>PV</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>NkT</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>, to find <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>N</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>.</para>
